  {"t":"tip","head":"Best time to visit","html":"May–June and September–October are the sweet spot — warm, without August's peak heat or crowds. Barcelona's holiday season really runs six months, May to October, with August daytime temperatures around 27–31°C; winters are mild, with the thinnest crowds and lowest prices. One honest catch: August is also when a lot of the small, family-run bodegas in this guide close for a few weeks — check hours before building a trip around any single one."},
  {"t":"callout","head":"Traveling considerately in Barcelona","html":"This isn't abstract here. By 2017, surveys found roughly 60% of Barcelona residents felt the city had reached or exceeded what it could handle from tourism, and housing pressure from short-term rentals has been severe enough that the city has moved to phase out short-term tourist-apartment licenses. Park Güell's visitor cap and active limits on cruise arrivals are part of the same response. None of that means don't come — it means come a little differently: book a hotel rather than a short-term rental where you can, treat the residential streets around Park Güell and the Gòtic's courtyards as someone's home rather than a backdrop, and spend where this guide already points you — Sant Andreu, Gràcia, Horta-Guinardó — rather than only on the Rambla corridor. It's a better trip anyway."},
