  {"t":"lead","html":"Ask a Barcelona local where to eat and you will not hear La Rambla mentioned once. This is the guide to the other city — the one with vermouth on tap, anchovies on toast, and a bar that's been pouring absinthe since 1820."},
  {"t":"p","html":"The tourist-menu stretch — La Rambla, the Gòtic's main drag, anywhere with a tout holding laminated photos of paella — is almost never where you want to eat. The real scene is a short metro ride into Sant Andreu, Gràcia, Sants and the quieter lanes of El Born and El Raval: small bars, family-run bodegas and vermuterías where the menu is in Catalan and nobody's translated it for you. That's where this list lives."},
  {"t":"callout","head":"Start here: Bar Marsella","html":"Barcelona's most storied bar has been pouring drinks since <strong>1820</strong> — the original 19th-century interior is still intact, marble-topped tables and all, in the heart of El Raval. Regulars over the decades reportedly included Picasso, Dalí and Hemingway. Yes, it's on every list now, including this one — but it earned that. Order the house absinthe the old way, over a sugar cube, and take your time with it."},
  {"t":"h2","text":"What to order"},
  {"t":"p","html":"Barcelona's plate is Catalan and Mediterranean first, with a couple of borrowed classics in the mix. Here's what to actually order:"},
  {"t":"ul","items":[
    "<strong>Tapas</strong> — the default way to eat out: small shared plates, leaning Catalan/Mediterranean rather than classic Andalusian bar-tapas style.",
    "<strong>Pa amb tomàquet</strong> — bread rubbed with ripe tomato, olive oil and salt. The everyday table staple, and the truest 'when in Barcelona' bite there is.",
    "<strong>Patatas bravas</strong> — fried potatoes with spicy tomato sauce and garlic alioli. Every bar has an opinion on whose is best; that rivalry is half the fun.",
    "<strong>Jamón</strong> — cured ham, ibérico or serrano, sliced to order from the corner bodega to La Boqueria itself.",
    "<strong>Escalivada</strong> — smoky roasted eggplant, pepper and onion, dressed simply. A quiet highlight on most menus.",
    "<strong>Crema catalana</strong> — Catalonia's own torched-sugar custard, the local answer to crème brûlée (and older than it).",
    "<strong>Vermút</strong> — less a dish than a ritual. More on that below.",
  ]},
  {"t":"tip","head":"Fer el vermut — the Barcelona ritual","html":"On Saturday or Sunday around midday, locals don't do brunch — they do <strong>vermut</strong>: house vermouth on tap, poured over ice with a twist, with a few olives or anchovies on the side, usually before lunch rather than instead of it. Three spots on this list are built entirely around it: Vermuteria Oxiterraneo and Vermuteria Puigmartí below, plus <strong>La Vermuteria del Tano</strong> in Gràcia — a genuine hole-in-the-wall, always busy, standing room only. Go early, or wait."},
  {"t":"callout","head":"About the paella","html":"Worth knowing before you order it: <strong>paella is Valencian, not Catalan</strong> — a dish Barcelona serves well (and has its own noodle cousin of, <em>fideuà</em>) but didn't invent. That's not a red flag on its own, but a restaurant whose whole identity is 'paella + sangria + a tout on the pavement' is usually optimized for footfall, not flavor. If you want it anyway, La Taberna de la Barceloneta below does a version with a proper socarrat crust."},
  {"t":"h2","text":"Fifteen places worth crossing town for"},
